The Rifle is in overall very good condition, with some minor rust scale located upon the top of the barrel just behind the front barrel band and very light peppering throughout the entire blued finish of the rifle (When properly done, this rifle will clean up very well).History: Vetterli rifles were a series of Swiss army rifles used from 1869 to around 1890, but were later replaced with Schmidt–Rubin rifles. Modified Vetterli rifles were also used in the Italian Army.  The Swiss Vetterli rifle combined the American Winchester Model 1866's tubular magazine with a regular bolt featuring two opposed rear locking lugs, which was a brand new concept for the time. This different type of bolt system was a huge improvement over the much simpler Dreyse and Chassepot bolt actions. The Vetterli was also the first repeating bolt-action rifle to incorporate self-cocking, along with a small caliber bore. With the Swiss Federal Council's decision in early 1866 to equip the Swiss Army with breechloading repeating rifles, the Vetterli rifles, at the time of their introduction, were the most advanced military rifles in all of Europe. The Vetterli replaced the use of the out dated Amsler-Milbank rifles.Feed system: 12-round tubular magazine rifle, was also produced.
